Here's how to handle draft persistence using MAUI's lifecycle events:

**1. In `App.xaml.cs`, hook into the `Window` lifecycle:**

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Deactivated += (s, e) =>
        WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Send(new AppBackgroundMessage());

    window.Activated += (s, e) =>
        WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Send(new AppResumedMessage());

    return window;
}
```

**2. Define simple messages:**

```csharp
public class AppBackgroundMessage { }
public class AppResumedMessage { }
```

**3. In your `NotesViewModel`, subscribe and persist via `Preferences`:**

```csharp
public partial class NotesViewModel : ObservableObject, IRecipient<AppBackgroundMessage>
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string draftText = string.Empty;

    private const string DraftKey = "notes_draft";

    public NotesViewModel()
    {
        // Restore any saved draft on construction
        DraftText = Preferences.Default.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);

        WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.RegisterAll(this);
    }

    public void Receive(AppBackgroundMessage message)
    {
        // Save draft when app goes to background
        Preferences.Default.Set(DraftKey, DraftText);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Window.Deactivated`** fires when the app loses focus (background). **`Window.Activated`** fires on resume.
- **`Preferences`** is ideal for small text. For larger drafts, use `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` with file I/O instead.
- **`WeakReferenceMessenger`** (from CommunityToolkit.Mvvm) decouples lifecycle events from your ViewModel — no tight coupling to `App`.
- You can also save on every keystroke (debounced) for extra safety, so a crash doesn't lose work:

```csharp
partial void OnDraftTextChanged(string value)
{
    _debounceTimer?.Cancel();
    _debounceTimer = Dispatcher.GetForCurrentThread()?.CreateTimer();
    _debounceTimer?.Start(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2), () =>
        Preferences.Default.Set(DraftKey, value));
}
```
